ontinued through 2008, but there have since been changes in the understanding and treatment of [[bipolar disorder|bipolar depressive disorder]]. In the show, Diana's doctor describes her as a \"bipolar depressive with delusional episodes\",<ref name=\"Tom Kitt 2009\">Music by Tom Kitt, & Book and Lyrics by Brian Yorkey. (2009). ''Next to normal [Feeling Electric]''. New York, NY: Musical Theatre International.</ref> however, the most recent edition of the [[American Psychiatric Association]]'s [[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders]] (DSM) would now diagnose Diana as bipolar \"with [[Psychosis|psychotic features]]\",<ref>Glass, Guy. (2015). \"[http://medhum.med.nyu.edu/view/16093 Next to Normal]\". ''NYU Langone Health''.</ref> referring to the [[hallucination]]s she experiences, such as of her dead son Gabe in the form of a teenager. The disorder is also now separated into bipolar types I and II.\n\n===Treatment===\n{{main|Treatment of bipolar disorder}}\n[[Bipolar disorder]] is a disease of both [[mania]] (or [[hypomania]]) and depression that is not curable, mostly treated through psychopharmacological, psychotherapeutic, and biological means. First, are the [[Psychopharmacology|psychopharmacological therapies]], commonly known as [[Pharmacotherapy|drug therapies]], which involves the use of [[antipsychotic]], [[anticonvulsant]], and [[antidepressant]] medications, that aim to stabilize the patient's mood. Such drugs include [[Lithium (medication)|Lithium]], a mood stabilizer, [[Lorazepam|Ativan]] and [[Diazepam|Valium]], benzodiazepines, all of which are mentioned in the lyrics, particularly in the song \"My Psychopharmacologist and I\", in which Diana is prescribed a plethora of different drugs at once, which are mentioned alongside their side-effects, ranging from drowsiness to [[sexual dysfunction]]. Another form of treatment the play explores is [[psychotherapy]], where patients talk to psychologists or other licensed mental health professionals and aim to work through the psychological component of their disease through conversation; Diana's psychiatrist leads her through a [[guided meditation]] or [[hypnotherapy|hypnotherapeutic]] approach. The third form addressed is [[Electroconvulsive therapy|electroconvulsive therapy (ECT)]] in which seizures are induced by sending an electric current through the brain. Following a suicide attempt, Diana is convinced to undergo ECT and then loses her memory (including her memory of Gabe), which she slowly gains back in talks with her family. ECT is often viewed as a last-resort option for depressed patients who are incredibly ill and extremely treatment-resistant or whose symptoms include very serious suicidal or psychotic symptoms, or for pregnant women.<ref>Hirschfeld, Robert, et al. Practice Guidelines for the Treatment of Patients with Bipolar Disorder Second Edition. Arlington, VA: American Psychiatric Association, 2002. Print.</ref> This practice holds true in the play, in which ECT is only recommended after Diana's hallucination of Gabe suggests that she kill herself in the song \"There's a World\".\n\n==Productions==\n\n===Development===\nThe musical began in 1998 as a 10-minute workshop sketch about a woman undergoing electroshock therapy, and its impact on her family, called ''Feeling Electric''.  Yorkey brought the idea to Kitt while both were at the BMI Lehman Engel Musical Theatre Workshop.  Kitt wrote a rock score for the short piece, which was highly critical of the medical treatment.  Both Yorkey and Kitt turned to other projects, but they \"kept returning to ''Feeling Electric''\", eventually expanding it to a full-length musical.<ref name=Columbia>Getlin, Josh.  \"The Ballad of Kitt &Yorkey\", ''Columbia Magazine'', [[Columbia University]], Fall 2010, pp. 22\u201323</ref>  This had a reading in 2002 at the [[Village Theatre]] in [[Issaquah, Washington]], then at several venues in New York City,<ref name=Columbia/> with a cast that included [[Norbert Leo Butz]] as Dan, [[Sherie Rene Scott]] as Diana, Benjamin Schrader as Gabe, Anya Singleton as Natalie and Greg Naughton as Dr. Madden. A subsequent staged reading was held in late 2002 at the Musical Mondays Theater Lab in New York.<ref>Jones, Kenneth. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/72517.html \"Feeling Electric, Butz and Larsen Sing Electro-Shock Therapy Musical Oct. 7\"] playbill.com, October 4, 2002</ref>\n\nIn 2005 it was workshopped again at [[Village Theatre]] starring [[Amy Spanger]] as Diana, Jason Collins as Dan, [[Mary Faber]] as Natalie and [[Deven May]] as Dr. Madden.<ref>Jones, Kenneth. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/93639.html \"Musical Workshop of ''Feeling Electric'', About a Frazzled Family, Stars a Bat Boy and a Lois Lane in Seattle\"], Playbill.com, June 21, 2005</ref>  In September 2005, the musical ran at the [[New York Musical Theatre Festival]], with Spanger as Diana, Joe Cassidy as Dan, [[Annaleigh Ashford]] as Natalie, Benjamin Schrader as Gabe and [[Anthony Rapp]] as Dr. Madden. This attracted the attention of producer [[David Stone (producer)|David Stone]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Jones|first=Kenneth|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/95066.html|title=Rapp & Spanger Help Spark Premiere of ''Feeling Electric'' Sept. 14-24 in NYMF|work=Playbill|date=September 14, 2005|accessdate=May 4, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115100758/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/rapp-spanger-help-spark-premiere-of-feeling-electric-sept.-14-24-in-nymf-128006|archivedate=January 15, 2016}}</ref> [[Second Stage Theatre]] then workshopped the piece in both 2006 and 2007, featuring Cassidy and then [[Gregg Edelman]] as Dan, Alice Ripley as Diana, [[Mary Faber]] and then [[Phoebe Strole]] as Natalie, Rapp as Dr. Madden/Dr. Fine and [[Skylar Astin]] as Henry.{{Citation needed|date=February 2009}}  Meanwhile, at the urging of Stone and director [[Michael Greif]], who had joined the team, the creators focused the show on the family's pain rather than on the critique of the medical establishment.<ref name=Columbia/>\n\n===Off-Broadway and Virginia (2008\u201309)===\n''Next to Normal'' was first produced [[Off-Broadway]] at the Second Stage Theatre from January 16 through March 16, 2008, directed by Greif, with [[Anthony Rapp]] as assistant director and musical staging by [[Sergio Trujillo]]. The cast featured Ripley as Diana, [[Brian d'Arcy James]] as Dan, [[Aaron Tveit]] as Gabe, [[Jennifer Damiano]] as Natalie, [[Adam Chanler-Berat]] as Henry and [[Asa Somers]] as Dr. Madden/Dr. Fine. The surname of the family was changed from Brown to Goodman.<ref>Hernandez, Ernio. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/115932.html \"New Musical ''Next to Normal'' Closes Off-Broadway March 16\"], playbill.com, March 16, 2008</ref>  Although the show received mixed reviews,<ref>Dziemianowicz, Joe. [http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/arts/2008/02/14/2008-02-14_the_high__low_notes_of_a_bipolar_mom_in_.html \"The high & low notes of a bipolar mom in ''next to normal''\"], ''New York Daily News'', February 14, 2008</ref><ref>Brantley, Ben. [http://theater2.nytimes.com/2008/02/14/theater/reviews/14normal.html?scp=6&sq=Next%20to%20Normal%20off-broadway%20review&st=cse \"There, Amid the Music, a Mind Is on the Edge\"], ''The New York Times'', February 14, 2008</ref> at least one reviewer criticized it for pushing an irresponsible message about the treatment of bipolar disorder and for failing to strike the proper balance between pathos and comedy.<ref>Caggiano, Chris.  [http://ccaggiano.typepad.com/everything_i_know_i_learn/2008/02/next-to-norma-1.html \"Next to Normal: Shaky Show, Irresponsible Message\"], Everything I Know I Learned from Musicals site, February 24, 2008</ref> The critics found the show internally confused, and the team decided to make major changes in both the book and score, including eliminating the original title song, \"Feeling Electric\".  They concentrated the story entirely on the emotions of Diana and her family as they confront bitter truths.<ref name=Columbia/>\n\nThe re-written musical was given a [[Regional theatre in the United States|regional theatre]] production at the [[Arena Stage]] (normally in Washington, D.C. but operating in Virginia during a renovation of its main facility), from November 21, 2008 through January 18, 2009, under the direction of Greif. [[J. Robert Spencer]] took over the role of Dan while [[Louis Hobson]] assumed the roles of Dr. Madden/Dr. Fine; the remaining Off-Broadway leads returned.<ref>Gans, Andrew. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/122253.html \"Chanler-Berat, Damiano, Hobson, Tveit Will Join Ripley and Spencer in Arena's ''Next to Normal''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090330044556/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/126642.html |date=March 30, 2009 }}, Playbill.com, October 10, 2008</ref> The production received rave reviews, with critics noticing that \"comic songs and glitzy production numbers\" had been replaced by songs that complemented the emotional content of the book.<ref>Marks, Peter. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/12/11/AR2008121103978.html \"Revised Musical Hits Home: Moving, Beautiful ''next to normal''\"], ''Washington Post'', December 12, 2008</ref><ref>Blanchard, Jayne. [http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2008/dec/15/next-to-terrific-at-arena/ \"Next to Terrific at Arena\"], ''Washington Times'', December 15, 2008</ref>\n\n===Broadway (2009\u201311)===\n''Next to Normal'' began previews on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] at the [[Booth Theatre]] on March 27, 2009, with an opening night of April 15. The entire cast from the Arena Stage production returned, once again under the direction of Greif.  The musical was originally booked for the larger [[Longacre Theatre]], but, according to producer David Stone, \"When the Booth Theatre became available... we knew it was the right space for ''Next to Normal''\".<ref>Gans, Andrew. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/126376.html \"''Next to Normal'', with Entire Arena Cast, to Play Broadway's Longacre\"], playbill.com, February 17, 2009</ref><ref>Gans, Andrew. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/126642.html \"''next to normal'' Will Now Play the Booth Theatre\"], playbill.com, February 24, 2009</ref>\n\nReviews were very favorable. [[Ben Brantley]] of ''The New York Times'' wrote that the Broadway production is \"A brave, breathtaking musical. It is something much more than a feel-good musical: it is a feel-everything musical.\"<ref>Brantley, Ben. [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/16/theater/reviews/16norm.html?_r=2&ref=theater \"Fragmented Psyches, Uncomfortable Emotions: Sing Out!\"], ''The New York Times'', April 16, 2009</ref>\n''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called it \"The best new musical of the season&nbsp;\u2013 by a mile.\"<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/blogs/traverstake/2009/04/next-to-normal-proves-that-roc.php#more \"The Travers Take: ''next to normal'' Proves that Rock is Thriving on Broadway\"], rollingstone.com, April 16, 2009</ref> ''Next to Normal'' was on the Ten Best of the Year list for 2009 of \"Curtain Up\".<ref>Sommer, Elyse and Saltzman, Simon. [http://www.curtainup.com/bestandworst2009.html#Ten%20Best%20of%20the%20Year  \"The Best (and Worst) of the Year 2009 On and Off Broadway\"] curtainup.com, retrieved January 9, 2010</ref>\n\nThe show set a new box office record at the Booth Theatre for the week ending January 3, 2010, grossing $550,409 over nine performances. The previous record was held by the 2006 production of Brian Friel's ''Faith Healer'', with a gross of $530,702.<ref>[http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/NEXT_TO_NORMAL_Breaks_Box_Office_Record_at_the_Booth_Theatre_20100104 \"''Next to Normal'' Breaks Box Office Record at the Booth Theatre\"], BroadwayWorld, 2010</ref> One year later, ''Next to Normal'' broke that record again during its final week on Broadway (week ending January 16, 2011) grossing $552,563 over eight performances.<ref>[http://broadwayworld.com/article/NEXT_TO_NORMAL_Breaks_Box_Office_Record_at_Booth_Theatre_20110118 \"''Next to Normal'' Breaks Box Office Record at the Booth Theatre\"], BroadwayWorld, 2011</ref> The producers recouped their initial investment of $4 million a few days after the production's one-year anniversary on Broadway.<ref>Healy, Patrick. [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/29/theater/29normal.html \"Broadway\u2019s Unlikely Hit Gives Hope to the Bold\"] ''New York Times'', March 28, 2010</ref> At the end of its run, ''Next to Normal'' grossed $31,764,486, the most out of all the shows that have run at the Booth Theatre, earning double the amount of money as its closest competition, ''I'm Not Rappaport''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://broadwayworld.com/grossestheater.cfm?theater=BOOTH&sortby=totaltotalGross&orderby=asc|title=BOOTH Broadway Grosses|website=broadwayworld.com|accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nCast replacements during the run included [[Marin Mazzie]] as Diana, Brian d'Arcy James<ref>[http://www.playbill.com/article/brian-darcy-james-will-rejoin-normal-cast-in-may-com-164609 \"Brian d'Arcy James Will Rejoin Normal Cast in May\"] playbill.com</ref> and later [[Jason Danieley]] as Dan, [[Kyle Dean Massey]] as Gabe and [[Meghann Fahy]] as Natalie.<ref name=times1>Healy, Patrick.  [http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/06/03/new-casting-announced-for-next-to-normal/  \"New Casting Announced for ''Next to Normal'']. ''The New York Times'', June 3, 2010</ref>  [[John Kenrick (theatre writer)|John Kenrick]] wrote in November 2010 that the show \"is glowing with breathtaking brilliance as it ends its Broadway run.\"<ref>Kenrick, John. [http://www.musicals101.com/nextnormal.htm ''Next to Normal'']. Musicals101.com, November 2010, accessed January 20, 2011</ref>\n\nThe Broadway production closed on January 16, 2011 after 21 previews and 733 regular performances.<ref>[http://broadwayworld.com/article/NEXT_TO_NORMAL_to_Close_on_Broadway_January_16_20101110 \"''Next to Normal'' to Close on Broadway January 16, 2011\"].  BroadwayWorld, November 10, 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/144815-Next-to-Normal-to-Close-on-Broadway-Jan-16-2011 \"''Next to Normal'' to Close on Broadway Jan 16, 2011\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101113192200/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/144815-Next-to-Normal-to-Close-on-Broadway-Jan-16-2011 |date=November 13, 2010 }}, Playbill</ref>\n\n==== Twitter promotional campaign ====\nIn May 2009, about six weeks into the Broadway run, ''Next to Normal'' began publishing an adapted version of the script over [[Twitter]], the social media network. Over 35 days, the serialized version of the show was published, a single line from a character at a time. The [[Twitter]] promotion ended the morning of June 7, 2009, the morning of the [[63rd Tony Awards]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/17/technology/internet/17normal.html?_r=2&scp=1&sq=%22next%20to%20normal%22&st=cse \"It's Broadway Gone Viral, With a Musical Meted Out via Twitter\"], ''The New York Times'', August 16, 2009.</ref> The initiative earned the musical the 2009 OMMA Award for Best in Show.<ref>[http://www.mediapost.com/events/?/showID/OMMAAwards.09.NewYorkCity] mediapost.com</ref>\n\n===First US tour (2010\u201311)===\n''Next to Normal'' began its first national tour of North America and Canada at the [[Ahmanson Theatre]] in [[Los Angeles]], California on November 23, 2010. The tour played in 16 cities in the U.S., ending in Toronto, Ontario, Canada on July 30, 2011. Alice Ripley reprised her role as Diana and was joined by Asa Somers as Dan, Emma Hunton as Natalie, [[Curt Hansen (actor)|Curt Hansen]] as Gabe, Preston K. Sadleir as Henry and [[Jeremy Kushnier]] as Dr. Madden/Dr. Fine.<ref>Hetrick, Adam.  [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/144132-Somers-Hunton-Hansen-Sadleir-and-Kushnier-to-Join-Ripley-for-Next-to-Normal-Tour?sms_ss=twitter&at_xt=4cbf1f35b0c9049c,0 \"Somers, Hunton, Hansen, Sadleir and Kushnier to Join Ripley for ''Next to Normal'' Tour\"].  Playbill.com, October 20, 2010</ref><ref>Fullerton, Krissie. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/145339-PHOTO-CALL-A-First-Look-at-the-Next-to-Normal-National-Tour-with-Alice-Ripley-Emma-Hunton-and-More \"Photo Call:A First Look at the 'Next to Normal' National Tour with Alice Ripley, Emma Hunton and More\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203010555/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/145339-PHOTO-CALL-A-First-Look-at-the-Next-to-Normal-National-Tour-with-Alice-Ripley-Emma-Hunton-and-More |date=December 3, 2010 }}. playbill.com, November 29, 2010</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nexttonormal.com/tour_cast |title=Archived copy |accessdate=April 17, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006201738/http://nexttonormal.com/tour_cast |archivedate=October 6, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n=== East West Players (2017) ===\n[[East West Players]] (EWP) produced a diverse and inclusive version of the musical featuring a cast with nearly all artists of color as a part of their 51st season under the direction of Nancy Keystone. The production was originally slated to run from May 12 to June 11, 2018, but was extended a week through June 28 due to high demand. The show's popularity carried into awards season, earning the production four of the major awards at the 2018 [[Ovation Awards]] including Best Production of a Musical (Large Theater), Best Featured Actress in a Musical, Best Lead Actress in a Musical, and Direction in a Musical; additionally, the Set/Projection Designer for the show, Hana Kim, was honored with the Sherwood Award which seeks \"to nurture innovative and adventurous theatre artists working in Los Angeles.\"<ref name=\"Wood\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.eastwestplayers.org/news/congratulations-to-the-company-of-next-to-normal/|title=Congratulations to the company of NEXT TO NORMAL!|last=Wood|first=Xim\u00f3n|website=East West Players|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref> Deedee Magno Hall played the leading role of Diana alongside her real-life husband Cliffton Hall, who played Diana's husband, Dan. [[Isa Briones]] won for her portrayal of Natalie.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gelt|first=Jessica|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-et-sm-ovation-awards-2018-story.html|title=Ovation Awards 2018: Wins for Actors Co-op's ''33 Variations'', East West Players' ''Next to Normal''|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 30, 2018|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe show was praised for its subject matter and the way in which the musical's exploration of mental health tied in seamlessly with its all-Asian cast.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@jenapherjunyizheng/next-to-normal-is-the-show-about-mental-health-all-asian-americans-need-to-see-91f66d74dff2|title='Next to Normal' is the show about mental health all Asian-Americans need to see|last=Zheng|first=Jenapher Jun-Yi|date=2017-05-29|website=Medium|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref> Mental health awareness is particularly stigmatized within areas of the [[Asian Pacific American|Asian Pacific-Islander]] community as a result of conflicting cultural and familial emphases.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kramer|first=Elizabeth J|last2=Kwong|first2=Kenny|last3=Lee|first3=Evelyn|last4=Chung|first4=Henry|date=September 2002|title=Cultural factors influencing the mental health of Asian Americans|journal=Western Journal of Medicine|volume=176|issue=4|pages=227\u2013231|issn=0093-0415|pmc=1071736|pmid=12208826}}</ref> EWP's producing artistic director Snehal Desai made a point to belabor the importance of \"shedding light on the stigma of mental illness in our communities,\" and that he hoped that the production could create \"a space for that conversation.\"<ref name=\"Wood\"/>\n\n=== Kennedy Center (2020) ===\n[[Rachel Bay Jones]] and [[Brandon Victor Dixon]] joined original Broadway director Greif for the Broadway Center Stage production at the [[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts]] in Washington, D.C. from January 29-February 3, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kennedy-center.org/press-releases/next-to-normal/|title=Next to Normal {{!}} Kennedy Center|website=www.kennedy-center.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\n==International==\n''Note: The following are independent productions of the musical produced internationally and in most cases, in that native language. They also feature the original music, lyrics and book, but changes in other aspects including direction, set design, costume design and choreography.\n\n===Scandinavia ===\nThe European premiere and the first non-English language production opened in September 2010 at the Det Norske Teatret in [[Oslo]], [[Norway]] under the direction of Svein Sturla Hungnes. The cast included [[Heidi Gjermundsen Broch]] as Diana and [[Charlotte Frogner]] as Natalie<ref>[http://www.detnorsketeatret.no/Default.aspx?Tabid=65&PlayId=373\"], Det Norske Teatret</ref> Broch received the 2011 Hedda Award (Norway's highest theatrical accolade) for her portrayal. This production was later re-staged for a Swedish premiere at the Wermland Opera<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wermlandopera.com/evenemang/next-to-normal|title=Next to Normal - Wermland Opera|website=www.wermlandopera.com|accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref> A Finnish production opened in December 2010 in [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]] at Studio Pasila, where it ran for one year.<ref>[http://www.hkt.fi/ohjelmisto/play.php?name=next] Helsinki City Theatre</ref> A Swedish-language production opened in September 2012 at Wasa Teater in [[Vaasa]], Finland. The cast included [[Anna-Maria Hallgarn]] as Diana.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wasateater.fi/information_plays.php?info_id=38 |title=Archived copy |access-date=September 22, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109051512/http://www.wasateater.fi/information_plays.php/?info_id=38 |archive-date=January 9, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Another Finnish-language production was staged at the [[Tampere Workers' Theatre]] from October 2012 through February 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ttt-teatteri.fi/ohjelmisto/next-normal|title=Tampereen Ty\u00f6v\u00e4en Teatteri - NEXT TO NORMAL|publisher=|accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref> A Danish production ran from February 2012 until April 2012 at N\u00f8rrebro Teater in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nbt.dk/da-DK/Forestillinger/Next+to+Normal.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=June 9, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110519073541/http://www.nbt.dk/da-DK/Forestillinger/Next+to+Normal.aspx |archive-date=May 19, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nA subsequent Swedish production also opened in September 2012 at the City Theatre of [[Stockholm]], Sweden, with [[Lisa Nilsson]] as Diana{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n===Asia ===\nThe Asian premiere was staged at the Carlos P. Romulo Auditorium, RCBC Plaza, [[Makati]], [[Philippines]] in March 2011 and again in October 2011. The cast included [[Markki Stroem]] as Henry.<ref>[http://philippines.broadwayworld.com/article/Manila_Markki_Stroem_Makes_Stage_Debut_In_NEXT_TO_NORMAL_31127_20110111] Philippines Broadway World</ref> [[Kolleen Park]] played Diana in the 2011 Korean production<ref>http://www.nexttonormal.co.kr</ref> ''Next to Normal ''premiered in Singapore on September 5, 2013, at the Drama Centre Theatre. The cast included [[Sally Ann Triplett]] as Diana, [[Adrian Pang]] as Dan, and [[Nathan Hartono]] as Gabe.<ref>{{citation|last=Gioia|first=Michael|title=Singapore Premiere of ''Next to Normal, ''Starring West End Actress Sally Ann Triplett, Begins Sept. 5|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/singapore-premiere-of-next-to-normal-starring-west-end-actress-sally-ann-triplett-begins-sept-5-com-209111|website=Playbill.com|date=September 9, 2013|accessdate=April 17, 2017}}</ref> A Chinese production premiered in Beijing, China, on August 3, 2018, and later played in Shanghai in December.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u65b0\u5267\u9884\u544a\uff01\u767e\u8001\u6c47\u97f3\u4e50\u5267\u300a\u8fd1\u4e4e\u6b63\u5e38\u300b\u4e2d\u6587\u72488\u67083\u65e5\u5728\u5317\u4eac\u9707\u64bc\u9996\u6f14|url=http://www.imusical.cn/2018/07/24/next-to-normal-will-come-to-beijing-in-august/|trans-title=New Musical: Broadway Musical ''Next to Normal'' 's Chinese production to premiere in Beijing on August 3 |accessdate=8 December 2018 |publisher=iMusical |date=24 July 2018 |language=zh-CN}}</ref>\n\n===Australia ===\nThe Australian premiere of the musical by the [[Melbourne Theatre Company]] was staged in [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]]. Performances began on April 28, 2012, and ran through June 4 (extended from May 28). The cast included [[Kate Kendall]] as Diana, [[Matt Hetherington]] as Dan and [[Bert LaBonte]] as Dr. Fine/Dr. Madden.<ref>[http://www.mtc.com.au/tickets/production.aspx?performanceNumber=3190 \"Listing, 'Next to Normal'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110130033242/http://www.mtc.com.au/tickets/production.aspx?performanceNumber=3190 |date=January 30, 2011 }} Melbourne Theatre Company, retrieved December 4, 2010</ref>\n\nA production in Perth played at the [[State Theatre Centre of Western Australia|Heath Ledger Theatre]] from November 5\u201319, 2015. Produced by [[Black Swan State Theatre Company]], the cast included [[Rachael Beck]] as Diana and Brendan Hanson as Dan.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Julia Hern|title=Next To Normal Black Swan Theatre Company|url=http://www.australianstage.com.au/201511127508/reviews/perth/next-to-normal-%7C-black-swan-state-theatre-company.html|website=Australian Stage|publisher=Australian Stage Online|accessdate=February 2, 2016|date=November 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===America ===\nA Spanish-language [[Peruvian]] premiere of the musical played the Teatro Marsano, in [[Lima]], [[Peru]]. The production ran from May to June 2011. The cast included [[Gisela Ponce de Le\u00f3n]] as Natalie<ref>[http://www.andina.com.pe/Espanol/Noticia.aspx?Id=TJlAr2hdo7M= Obra musical de Broadway], \"Casi normal\" se estrena por primera vez en Lima traducida al espa\u00f1ol</ref> The [[Argentina|Argentinian]] adaptation, titled \"Casi Normales\", played [[Buenos Aires]] from January 3, 2012 to April 5, 2015. The cast included [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Bartolilla]]  as Gabe.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}} A [[Brazil]]ian production opened in July 2012 at the Clara Nunes Theatre in [[Rio de Janeiro]], under the title \"Quase Normal\", which translates ''Almost Normal''.<ref>[http://estamosaquiproducoes.com.br/quasenormal.html] Estamos Aqui Produ\u00e7\u00f5es - Quase Normal http://estamosaquiproducoes.com.br/quasenormal.html</ref> A Mexican production opened at the Teatro Aldama in [[Mexico City]] on January 31, 2019, starring [[Susana Zabaleta]] as Diana.<ref>[https://acironline.mx/sin-categoria/casi-normales-el-musical-bipolar-que-te-conquistara/ \"Casi normales, el musical bipolar que te conquistar\u00e1\"], acironline.mx, February 1, 2019</ref>\n\n===Europe===\nThe [[Netherlands|Dutch]] premiere took place on January 16, 2012 at DeLaMar Theater in [[Amsterdam]]. The cast included [[Simone Kleinsma]] as Diana.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.musicals.nl/nexttonormal |title=Archived copy |access-date=September 14, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927200645/http://musicals.nl/nexttonormal/ |archive-date=September 27, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A German-language production opened at the Stadttheater in [[F\u00fcrth]], [[Bavaria]], on October 11, 2013. [[Pia Douwes]] starred in the role of Diana with [[Thomas Borchert]] as Dan.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}} The Italian version of the show, produced by STM and directed by Marco Iacomelli, opened on March 7, 2015 at Teatro Coccia in [[Novara]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nexttonormal.it|title=Next to Normal \u2013 Italia|last=Italia|first=Next to Normal|website=www.nexttonormal.it|access-date=April 18, 2017}}</ref> A Spanish-language production opened at the Teatro P\u00e9rez Gald\u00f3s in [[Las Palmas]], [[Canary Islands]], on September 14, 2017, starring [[Nina (Spanish singer)|Nina]] as Diana, and then it toured through Spain with stops at [[Barcelona]], [[Bilbao]], and [[Madrid]].<ref>[http://www.laprovincia.es/cultura/2017/09/14/normales-despega-galdos-busca-exito/977324.html \"Casi normales despega en el Gald\u00f3s en busca del \u00e9xito nacional\"], laprovincia.es, September 14, 2017</ref> In 2016, in Portugal, opened a Portuguese-speaking version, with the title \"Quase Normal\". A Russian-language production (\"\u041d\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043a\u043e \u043e\u0442 \u041d\u043e\u0440\u043c\u044b\"), directed by Anastasia Grinenko, opened in Minsk, Belarus on March 28, 2018, with Svetlana Matsievskaia starring as Diana.<ref>https://musicals.by/production/next-to-normal/</ref>\n\n==Casts==\n''Note: Below are the principal casts of all official major productions of the musical.''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"80%\"\n! Role\n! Original Broadway cast\n! Original US tour cast\n! Kennedy Center cast\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Diana Goodman\n| align=\"center\" colspan=\"2\"| [[Alice Ripley]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Rachel Bay Jones]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Dan Goodman\n| align=\"center\" |[[J. Robert Spencer]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Asa Somers]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Brandon Victor Dixon]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Natalie Goodman\n| align=\"center\"| [[Jennifer Damiano]]\n| align=\"center\" |Emma Hunton\n| align=\"center\" |Maia Reficco\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Gabriel \"Gabe\" Goodman\n| align=\"center\"| [[Aaron Tveit]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Curt Hansen (actor)|Curt Hansen]]\n| align=\"center\" |Khamary Rose\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Henry\n| align=\"center\"| [[Adam Chanler-Berat]]\n| align=\"center\" |Preston K. Sadleir\n| align=\"center\" |[[Ben Levi Ross]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Dr. Fine/Dr. Madden\n| align=\"center\"| [[Louis Hobson]]\n|align=\"center\" | [[Jeremy Kushnier]]\n| align=\"center\"| [[Michael Park (actor)|Michael Park]]\n|-\n|}\n\n;Notable Broadway replacements\n*Gabriel \"Gabe\" Goodman: [[Kyle Dean Massey]]\n*Dan Goodman: [[Brian d'Arcy James]], [[Jason Danieley]] \n*Diana Goodman: [[Marin Mazzie]]\n*Natalie Goodman: [[Meghann Fahy]]\n\n==Literary references and allusions==\n*During Act I, Gabe reads a paperback copy of ''[[The Catcher in the Rye]]''. Kyle Dean Massey said, \"I read about a page a night.\" Salinger's novel about grieving a loss is read by the character who ''is'' the loss.  In ''Catcher'', Holden struggles with the loss of a brother, Allie, who died of leukemia.\n*When sorting through a box of items from her son's room, Diana picks up a music box from the box to reveal a copy of ''[[Goodnight Moon]]'' underneath.\n*Natalie carries a hardcover copy of ''[[Flowers for Algernon]]'', which she is studying in school. Both the novel and \"Next to Normal\" deal with psychological experimentation.\n*Diana alludes to ''[[One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest (film)|One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest]]'', [[Sylvia Plath]], and [[Frances Farmer]] in the song \"Didn't I See This Movie?\".\n*Diana also reads from ''[[Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?]]'', a play by [[Edward Albee]] which deals with marital stress caused by issues similar to some in \"Next to Normal\". On her YouTube site, Alice Ripley said that she uses Albee's play as a Bible, drawing inspiration for Diana.\n\n==Pulitzer Prize controversy==\n''Next to Normal'' won the 2010 [[Pulitzer Prize for Drama]] although it was not on the shortlist of three candidates submitted to the twenty-member Pulitzer Prize board by the five-member Drama jury. Jury chairman and critic [[Charles McNulty]] publicly criticized the Board for overlooking those three plays, which were not running on Broadway at the time of the Award, in favor of one that was.<ref>[http://theenvelope.latimes.com/la-et-pulitzer-mcnulty-20100413,0,3224899.story] ''Los Angeles Times'' {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100415050116/http://theenvelope.latimes.com/la-et-pulitzer-mcnulty-20100413,0,3224899.story|date=April 15, 2010}}</ref><ref>Hetrick, Adam.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/138706-Pulitzer-Drama-Juror-David-Rooney-Weighs-In-On-Next-to-Normal-Win \"Pulitzer Drama Juror David Rooney Weighs In On Next to Normal Win\"] playbill.com, April 13, 2010</ref><ref>[[Simonson, Robert]].[http://www.playbill.com/features/article/138796-PLAYBILLCOMS-THEATRE-WEEK-IN-REVIEW-April-10-April-16-The-Pulitzer-Paradox \"Playbill.com's Theatre Week In Review, April 10-April 16: The Pulitzer Paradox\"] playbill.com, April 16, 2010</ref><!-- response? commentary? -->\n\n==Major awards and nominations==\n\n===Original Off-Broadway production===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"95%\"\n|-\n! width=\"5%\"| Year\n! width=\"20%\"| Award Ceremony\n! width=\"45%\"| Category\n! width=\"20%\"| Nominee\n! width=\"10%\"| Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"10\" align=\"center\"| 2008\n|rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|[[Drama League Award]]s\n|colspan=\"2\"|Distinguished Production of a Musical\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Distinguished Performance Award\n|[[Brian d'Arcy James]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"| [[Drama Desk Award]]\n| [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actress in a Musical|Outstanding Actress in a Musical]]\n| [[Alice Ripley]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Music|Outstanding Music]]\n| [[Tom Kitt (musician)|Tom Kitt]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan= \"3\" align= \"center\"|[[Outer Critics Circle Award]]s\n|Outstanding Actress in a Musical\n|Alice Ripley\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"|Outstanding New Off-Broadway Musical\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"|Outstanding New Score\n|{{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan= \"3\" align= \"center\"| [[Lucille Lortel Awards|The Lucille Lortel Awards]]\n|colspan=\"2\"|Outstanding Musical\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Outstanding Featured Actor\n|Aaron Tveit\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Outstanding Lighting Design\n|Kevin Adams\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n===Original Virginia production===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"95%\"\n|-\n! width=\"5%\"| Year\n! width=\"20%\"| Award Ceremony\n! width=\"45%\"| Category\n! width=\"20%\"| Nominee\n! width=\"10%\"| Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" align=\"center\"|2009\n| rowspan=\"5\" align=\"center\"|[[Helen Hayes Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"1\" colspan=\"2\"|Outstanding Non-Resident Production\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"|Outstanding Lead Actress, Non-Resident Production\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[Alice Ripley]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"|Outstanding Lead Actor, Non-Resident Production\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[J. Robert Spencer]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Outstanding Supporting Performer, Non-Resident Production\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[Jennifer Damiano]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[Aaron Tveit]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Original Broadway production===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"95%\"\n|-\n! width=\"5%\"| Year\n! width=\"20%\"| Award Ceremony\n! width=\"45%\"| Category\n! width=\"20%\"| Nominee\n! width=\"10%\"| Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"11\" align=\"center\"| 2009\n| rowspan=\"11\" align=\"center\"| [[Tony Award]]\n| colspan=\"2\"| [[Tony Award for Best Musical|Best Musical]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Tony Award for Best Book of a Musical|Best Book of a Musical]]\n| [[Brian Yorkey]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Tony Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] \n| [[Tom Kitt (musician)|Tom Kitt]] and Brian Yorkey\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Leading Actor in a Musical|Best Performance by a Leading Actor in a Musical]]\n| [[J. Robert Spencer]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Leading Actress in a Musical|Best Performance by a Leading Actress in a Musical]]\n| [[Alice Ripley]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Featured Actress in a Musical|Best Performance by a Featured Actress in a Musical]]\n| [[Jennifer Damiano]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Tony Award for Best Direction of a Musical|Best Direction of a Musical]]\n| [[Michael Greif]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Tony Award for Best Orchestrations|Best Orchestrations]]\n| [[Michael Starobin]] and [[Tom Kitt (musician)|Tom Kitt]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Tony Award for Best Scenic Design|Best Scenic Design]]\n| Mark Wendland\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Tony Award for Best Lighting Design|Best Lighting Design]]\n| [[Kevin Adams]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Tony Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n| Brian Ronan\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"| 2010\n| colspan=\"3\"| [[Pulitzer Prize for Drama]]\n| {{won}}\n|}\n<!--  Please include only prestigious critical awards, not audience awards. It trivializes the awards section. See [[WP:FANCRUFT]]-->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://nexttonormal.com Official Website]\n*{{ibdb show|id=483135|title=Next to Normal}}\n* ''[http://www.mtishows.com/show_detail.asp?showid=000383 Next to Normal]'' at the Music Theatre International website\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090806094923/http://www.nexttonormal.com/twitterperformance.pdf Twitter Performance Transcript]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100903024726/http://www.lortel.org/LLA_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&title=Next%20to%20Normal Lortel Archives listing]\n*[http://www.mynorthwest.com/?nid=82&sid=176221 Interview with Brian Yorkey] on [http://www.mynorthwest.com/?nid=1 MyNortwest.com]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/29/theater/29norm.html?_r=2&sq=an%20out-of-town%20overhall&st=cse&adxnnl=1&scp=1&adxnnlx=1241208101-X7n4hSeJruy6aNQYP9iMJQ NY Times Feature: An Out-of-Town Overhaul Helps Next to Normal Find Focus]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/19/theater/19cohe.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=mental%20illness,%20the%20musical&st=cse NY Times Feature: On Broadway, 'Next to Normal' Aims for Truth About Mental Illness]\n*[http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/arts/2009/04/16/2009-04-16_normal_is_way_beyond_ordinary.html Daily News Broadway review 2009]\n*[http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20272677,00.html Entertainment Weekly B